piped.video/cXXPRImhn_E Colbert rips apart Dershowitz's truly insane argument that@realdonaldtrump couldn't have done anything wrong because he believes his reelection is in the national interest.

@realDonaldTrump Senator Ted Cruz asked Trump’s defense team, “As a matter of law, does it matter if there was a ‘quid pro quo?’” Alan Dershowitz rose to answer the question. Although the hoped-for answer from Dershowitz was, “No” followed by a hasty retreat to his seat, the

loquacious Dershowitz could not restrain himself. He gave an answer that revealed the core of Trump’s defense: He said, in effect, if Trump acted in his own self-interest to interfere in the 2020 election, and if he believed his reelection was in the nation’s best interest, then

a quid pro quo is not impeachable. See CNN, “Alan Dershowitz argues presidential quid pro quos aimed at reelection are not impeachable.” (“And if a president did something that he believes will help him get elected, in the public interest, that cannot be the kind of quid pro quo

that results in impeachment.”) Dershowitz’s answer is stunning for three reasons. First, the argument asserts that Trump’s interest and the nation’s interest are one-and-the-same. It is the modern-day version of Louis XIV’s l'état, c'est moi—“I am the state.”

Second, Dershowitz admitted the core truth of Trump’s defense: If Trump doesn’t believe he did anything wrong, he can’t be impeached. Third, Dershowitz argued that the Senate is not even permitted to examine Trump’s intent.

Taken together, Dershowitz’s argument reduces to the absurd notion that a president can engage in a corrupt act as long as he subjectively believes it isn’t wrong—and we don’t get to examine evidence of the president’s intent. See Real Clear Politics, “Dershowitz: Not Impeachable

If President Does Something He Believes Will Help Him Get Elected In The Public Interest.” There you have it: For Republicans, Trump is king. Dershowitz gets credit for being honest but deserves opprobrium for making the most ridiculous argument to disgrace the floor of the
Senate in more than two centuries. He has embarrassed himself for all time. @jimcramer @tomkeene @morningmika @morning_joe @steverattner
